%I A389105 #68 May 17 2026 12:05:20
%S A389105 1,4,27,8,35,30,847,56,99,250,209,252,2587,1764,75,48,1037,328239090,
%T A389105 58159
%N A389105 a(n) is the smallest value of k such that gcd(A381466(k-1), k) = n.
%C A389105 Equivalently, a(n) is the first time n is a divisor at a division step of A381466; i.e., a(n) = the smallest value of k such that k/A381466(k) = n.
%C A389105 We conjecture that a(n) > 0 for all n; i.e., every positive integer is a divisor in A381466 at least once; indeed, we conjecture that every positive integer is a divisor infinitely many times. For positive values found so far, a(n) > 1.2^(n-1), and we also conjecture this is always true.
%C A389105 In the first 10^12 terms of A381466:
%C A389105   - there are 55 known terms up to a(106), see linked a-file;
%C A389105   - the smallest number that has not yet appeared as a divisor is 20;
%C A389105   - 106 is the largest unique divisor to appear at index 2028511506;
%C A389105   - 73 is the last number to appear as a new divisor at index 160322038411.
%H A389105 Sam Chapman, <a href="/A389105/a389105.txt">Table of n, a(n) for all terms < 10^12 (where ? denotes missing, larger values)</a>
%e A389105 a(2) = 4 because step 4 is the first time we divide by 2 in A381466.
%e A389105 a(3) = 27 because step 27 is the first time we divide by 3 in A381466.
%o A389105 (PARI) a(n) = my(k=1, v=4, g); while ((g=gcd(k, v)) != n, k++; if (g==1, v += k-1, v = (k-1)/g)); k; \\ _Michel Marcus_, May 17 2026
%Y A389105 Cf. A381466.
%K A389105 nonn,more,changed
%O A389105 1,2
%A A389105 _Sam Chapman_, Mar 11 2026
